@2:10 I call BS!  IF you're generating 6 volts at that very slight movement then you must be generating Nano-Amps.  I just bench tested a speaker with an oscilloscope.  Under more vigorous excitation I'm only seeing 80 mV (milli-volts) (That's 0.080 volts peak to peak).  That's a HUGE ways away from 6 to 18 volts you're claiming. 

@3:00 you call your sham device an alternator.  Well, yes, that's what it is - an alternator.  But if you're going to consider generating any kind of power from this, and you admit it's ultra low current, you're going to need significantly higher speed of movement of the coil and the magnetic field.

My bench test is no where near to what you're claiming.  You're virtually claiming free energy from the slightest bit of wind.  While you WILL see some electrical charge generated, the POWER of that charge is totally useless.

Your video is BS!

